</ref> and had been working part-time concurrently as a reporter for [[WDAS (AM)#WDAS|WDAS]],<ref name = "pi1"/> then an [[African American culture|African-American-oriented]] and minority-owned radio station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/nj2/piratejim/phillyamhistory.html|title=Philadelphia AM Radio History|publisher=Radio-History.com|accessdate=2007-10-30}}</ref>

== Arrest for murder and trial ==
{{main|1982 trial of Mumia Abu-Jamal}}
{{seealso|Mumia Abu-Jamal legal proceedings}}
[[Image:Daniel faulkner.jpg|right|thumb|Daniel Faulkner]] 
In the early hours of [[December 9]], [[1981]], around 3:51 a.m., [[Philadelphia Police Department]] officer [[Daniel Faulkner]] was shot and killed during an altercation that ensued from a routine traffic stop of a vehicle driven by [[William Cook (street vendor)|William Cook]], Abu-Jamal's younger brother. During the altercation Abu-Jamal was also shot and wounded. Officers arriving at the scene found a [[.38 Special|.38 caliber]] revolver beside Abu-Jamal that records show he had purchased in 1979. The cylinder of the revolver had five spent cartridges. He was taken directly from the scene of the shooting to a hospital and was treated for his injury. He was charged with the [[first-degree murder]] of Daniel Faulkner. He initially retained the services of criminal defense attorney Anthony Jackson.<ref name = "82t">{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =1982 trial and post-conviction relief hearing transcripts
 | work =
 | publisher =Commonwealth of Pennsylvania
 | date =
 | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
 | format =pdf
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> 

[[Image:Philadelphia City Hall (from Art Museum).JPG|thumb|right|Philadelphia City Hall, shown in 2006]]
The case went to trial in June 1982 at [[Philadelphia City Hall|Philadelphia's City Hall]]. The judge initially acquiesced to Abu-Jamal's request to represent himself, with Jackson continuing to act as his legal advisor. During the first day of the trial, however, Abu-Jamal repeatedly and vociferously dissented from accepting the judge's rulings on points of law to the extent that he was removed from representing himself and it was ordered that Jackson resume the role of acting as his sole advocate by reason of what the judge deemed to be intentionally disruptive actions on Abu-Jamal's part.<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript §1.72–§1.73
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 17]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-17-82.html 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-30}}</ref> In all, according to his detractors, Abu-Jamal was removed from the courtroom at least 13 times for disruption during the course of the legal proceedings and trial.<ref>{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =danielfaulkner.com summary of case facts (p. 2)
 | work =
 | publisher =Justice for Daniel Faulkner
 | date =
 | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/SummaryofCaseFacts.pdf
 | format =PDF
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref>

=== Prosecution case ===
The following sequence of events was presented in evidence by the prosecution before the jury at his trial:<ref name = "82t"/> 
# During the traffic stop, Cook assaulted Faulkner, who in turn attempted to subdue Cook.
# Abu Jamal emerged from a nearby parking lot, crossed the street, and shot Faulkner in the back.
# Faulkner was able to return fire, seriously wounding Abu-Jamal.
# Abu Jamal then advanced on Faulkner, fired some additional shots at close range, one of which struck Faulkner in the face causing his death.
# Abu Jamal was unable to flee due to his own gunshot wound, collapsed on a nearby curb, and was taken into custody by other police officers, who had been summoned by Faulkner at the time of the traffic stop.

====Eyewitnesses====
Four eyewitnesses to the shooting were produced by the prosecution:
# Robert Chobert, a disqualified/unlicensed cab driver on parole for [[arson]],<ref>{{cite web
| title = Trial Transcript §3.216
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher = Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 19]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-19-82.html#chobert
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> with two arrests for drunk-driving,<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript §3.226
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 19]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-19-82.html#chobert
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> who in 1995 admitted to having sought the advice of the trial prosecutor as to how he could reclaim his driving privileges;<ref>{{Citation
 | last = Handleman 
 | first = Scott
 | authorlink =
 | last2 =
 | first2 =
 | author2-link =
 | title =The Mumia Case, In True Colors
 | newspaper = Counterpunch
 | pages =
 | year =2003
 | date = April 26, 2003
 | url =http://www.counterpunch.org/handleman04262003.html}}</ref>
# Cynthia White, a prostitute;
# Michael Scanlon, a businessman who had been visiting from out of town on the night of the killing;
# Albert Magilton, a pedestrian.
These witnesses testified that they were at or in sight of the scene at the time of the shooting.

Robert Chobert was in his cab parked directly behind Faulkner's police car. He positively identified Abu-Jamal as the shooter, testifying: "I heard a shot. I looked up, I saw the cop fall to the ground, and then I saw Jamal standing over him and firing some more shots into him...Then I saw him [Jamal] walking back about ten feet and he just fell by the curb."<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript §3.210–§3.211
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date = [[June 19]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-19-82.html#chobert
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> During cross-examination, he admitted that he had originally told police that the shooter had moved 30 rather than 10&nbsp;ft away from Faulkner, and had been 30-to-50&nbsp;pounds heavier than Abu-Jamal. He explained, "I'm not good at weight. Do you think I'm going to stand there for a couple of minutes and ask him how much he weighs?"<ref name="chobert">{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript §3.235–§3.247
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 19]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-19-82.html#chobert
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> In his [[September 25]], [[2001]], affidavit private investigator George Newman describes that under interrogation Chobert had recanted the aspect of his testimony that his taxi had been parked directly behind Faulkner's police car as well as the assertion that he had witnessed a person firing bullets into the body of Faulkner as the latter lay prone on the ground.<ref>{{Citation
 | last =Newman
 | first =George Michael
 | authorlink =
 | last2 =
 | first2 =
 | author2-link =
 | title =Affidavit of George Michael Newman
 | newspaper = 
 | pages =
 | year =
 | date =[[September 25]], [[2001]] 
 | url =http://www.freemumia.com/newmandeclaration.html}}</ref>

Cynthia White testified to witnessing the shootings from a nearby corner. Describing Abu-Jamal's actions, she said: "he was running out of the parking lot and he was practically on the curb when he shot two times at the police officer. It was the back. The police officer turned around and staggered and seemed like he was grabbing for something. Then he fell. Then he came over and be came on top of the police officer and shot some more times. After that he went over and he slouched down and he sat on the curb."<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript pp.94-95
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 21]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-21-82.html#white
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> Dessie Hightower has stated that he observed her to be at least half a block further away.<ref name= "MAJCRD_DVD">{{cite video
| people = Mumia Abu-Jamal
| title = Mumia Abu-Jamal: A Case for Reasonable Doubt? 
| medium = DVD of HBO TV Special
| publisher = Otmoor Productions
| location = London, UK
| date = 1997 }}</ref> Prostitute Veronica Jones said later that she had been offered favorable treatment by police on condition that she corroborate Cynthia White.<ref name= "MAJCRD_DVD"/> In her declaration of [[January 28]], [[2002]], Yvette Williams affirmed to having been incarcerated with White in December 1981 and being told by her that she had not even seen who shot Faulkner and that she had entirely fabricated a witness account identifying Abu-Jamal out of fear of the Philidelphia police.<ref>{{Citation
 | last =Williams
 | first =Yvette
 | authorlink =
 | last2 =
 | first2 =
 | author2-link =
 | title =Declaration of Yvette Williams
 | newspaper = 
 | pages =
 | year =
 | date =[[January 28]], [[2002]] 
 | url = http://www.mumia.de/doc/aktuell/20020227mde01en.html}}</ref> Police informant [[Pamela Jenkins (informant)|Pamela Jenkins]] testified at a post-conviction relief hearing on [[June 26]], [[1997]], that she had been pressured by Philadelphia police offers to falsely state that she had witnessed the killing of Faulkner and to falsely identify Abu-Jamal as the murderer. She also testified that she knew White to be in fear of her life from police in the period after the shooting of Faulkner and before the trial of Abu-Jamal, and that she had tracked down and discovered Ms White in the company of some Philadelphia police as recently as March 1997.<ref>{{Citation
 | last = 
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | last2 =
 | first2 =
 | author2-link =
 | title =Post-conviction Relief Act hearing testimony of Pamela Jenkins. Commonwealth v Mumia Abu-Jamal, Court of Common Pleas, First Judicial District of Pennsylvania, Criminal Trial Division. 
 | newspaper = 
 | pages =
 | year =
 | date =[[June 26]], [[1997]] 
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/pcra/97-06-26.html}}</ref> However, the prosecution produced Cynthia White's death certificate showing that she had died in 1992.<ref>{{Cite web
 | last = 
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | title =Post-conviction Relief Act hearing. ''Commonwealth v Mumia Abu-Jamal aka Wesley Cook'', Court of Common Pleas, First Judicial District of Pennsylvania, Criminal Trial Division. 
 | year =
 | date =[[June 26]], [[1997]] 
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/pcra/97-06-26.html
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref>

Scanlan testified that he saw Faulkner assaulted in front of his police car shortly before another man ran across the street from a parking lot and shot Faulkner. Scanlan was not able to identify the shooter. Under cross-examination, which was interrupted by Abu-Jamal being removed from the courtroom for disruption, Scanlan admitted to being mildly under the influence of alcohol and was unable to describe in detail the appearance of the assailants.<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript pp.5-75
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 25]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-25-82.html#scanlan
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref>

Magilton testified to witnessing Faulkner pull over Cook's car and that at the point of seeing Abu-Jamal start to cross the street toward them from the parking lot he turned away and lost sight of what happened next until he heard gun shots. He did not see any shooting, or Chobert's vehicle parked behind Faulkner's.<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript pp.75-75
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 25]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-25-82.html#scanlan
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> He reported to defense investigators that he had seen a person wearing a green army jacket fleeing the scene in the aftermath.

==== Hospital confession ====
The prosecution presented two witnesses, security officer Priscilla Durham and Police Officer Garry Bell, who testified that while Abu-Jamal was at hospital, he acknowledged that he shot Faulkner by once or even twice proclaiming, "I shot the mother fucker, and I hope the mother fucker dies."<ref>{{cite web 
 | title = Trial Transcript pp.29, 31, 34, 137, 162 and 164
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 24]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-24-82.html
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> The hospital doctors are recorded as having said that Abu-Jamal was not capable of making such a statement during the time that he was reported to have uttered it.<ref name="guardian"/> The original report of Gary Wakshul, a police officer who confirms to having accompanied Abu-Jamal throughout the entire period of his arrest and medical treatment, relates that "the negro male made no comment". Wakshul elsewhere later chose to recall that he heard Abu-Jamal's utterance of the alleged confession on the night of the killing, such recollection first being offered almost three months after the arrest and upon the occasion when the prosecutor met with police seeking to test the evidence about any such utterance(s). He is recorded as having reasoned that he "didn't think the confession was important" at the time he wrote his original report. Judge [[Albert F. Sabo]] did not permit the trial jury to receive that report as evidence.<ref name = "82t">{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =1982 trial transcripts
 | work =
 | publisher =Commonwealth of Pennsylvania
 | date =
 | url =http://www.danielfaulkner.com/docs/MumiaTrialandPCRAAppealsTranscripts.pdf
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-18 }}
 </ref>

==== Physical evidence ==== 
A .38 caliber handgun Abu-Jamal had purchased to defend himself as a cab driver in 1979 was found at the scene next to him with 5 spent shell casings.<ref>{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =Developments in the Mumia Abu-Jamal case
 | work =
 | publisher =[[CNN.com]] 
 | date =[[December 18]] [[2001]]
 | url =http://archives.cnn.com/2001/LAW/12/18/chronology.abu.jamal 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-18}}</ref> Coroner Dr. Paul Hoyer, who [[autopsy|autopsied]] Daniel Faulkner, recorded in the examining report that he extracted a [[.44 Magnum|.44 caliber]] bullet noting "shot w/ 44 cal". He later testified to the effect that his description of it had been a "rough guess" based on his own observations, that he was not a firearms expert and that he had not received any training in weapons ballistics.<ref>Trial transcript for [[June 25]], [[1982]]</ref> 
Tests performed with the available physical evidence verify that Faulkner was killed by a .38 caliber bullet. The extracted slugs identified as [[Federal Cartridge|Federal brand]] [[.38 Special]] [[+P]] bullets with hollow bases. It may be noted that the hollow base in a +P bullet is distinguishable from Federal ammunition otherwise used at that time.<ref>{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =.38 Special LSWCHP +P: Still a Top Load? 
 | work =
 | publisher =Hipowersandhandguns.com
 | date =
 | url =http://www.hipowersandhandguns.com/38%20Special%20158gr%20LSWCHP.htm
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}</ref> The type, brand, and caliber of the extracted bullets all match those of the shell casings obtained from Abu-Jamal's [[Charter Arms]] revolver which was retrieved at the scene. That manufacturer is known for rifling the barrels of their revolvers with eight lands and grooves in a right-hand direction of twist - characteristics also evident on the bullet fragments extracted from Faulkner's body. Anthony L. Paul, Supervisor of the Firearms Identification Unit, testified at trial that he could name two other manufacturers "right off the bat" which produce weapons bearing the exact same rifling characteristics of pattern and twist direction.<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript p.169
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 23]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-23-82.html#paul 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}</ref> Experts testified that the bullet taken from Abu-Jamal had been fired from Faulkner's service weapon. George Fassnacht, a ballistics expert proferred by the defense, did not dispute any of the findings of the prosecution's weapons and ballistics experts.<ref name= "yn">{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =Mumia Abu-Jamal, Petitioner, v. Martin Horn, Commissioner, Pennsylvania Department of Corrections, et al., Respondents. Memorandum and Order (December 2001 US District Court ruling of Judge Yohn detailing the history, progression, and outcomes of all prior post-conviction appeals)
 | work =
 | publisher =US District Court for the Eastern District of Philadelphia
 | date =
 | url =http://www.paed.uscourts.gov/documents/opinions/01D0951P.pdf 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}</ref> 
[[Amnesty International]] has made reference to the physical evidence to the extent of expressing their view that there was: <blockquote>".. a lack of adequate [[Ballistic fingerprinting|ballistic tests]] to determine whether [Abu-Jamal's] gun had recently been fired. It was not determined, for instance, whether there was residue on his hands from firing a gun."<ref name = "amn"/></blockquote> In a 1995 hearing, another defense ballistics expert testified that due to Abu-Jamal's struggle with the police during his arrest, such a test would have been difficult to accomplish and, due to the gunpowder residue possibly being shaken or rubbed off, would not have been scientifically reliable.<ref>{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =COMMONWEALTH VS. MUMIA ABU-JAMAL aka WESLEY COOK - Post Conviction Review Act hearing transcripts of [[February 8]], [[1995]]
 | work =
 | publisher =Commonwealth of Pennsylvania
 | date =
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/pcra/95-08-02.html 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-18 }}</ref>

=== Defense case ===
The defense presented statements made by four witnesses describing the fact that one or more men were running along the street shortly after the shooting: Deborah Kordansky, Robert Chobert, Veronica Jones, and Dessie Hightower.<ref name = "82t"/> This became known as the "running man theory", based on the possibility that a "running man" may have been the actual shooter. Of those witnesses, only Chobert averred to actually witnessing the shooting. He testified that shortly after the shooting he had told police that he had seen Abu-Jamal shoot Faulkner in the face, and that Abu-Jamal had then run a short distance and collapsed on the sidewalk - himself having also been shot by Faulkner.<ref name = "chobert"/> The remaining three witnesses made various statements about a man or men running in or away from the area. None of them claimed that the running man, or men, were involved in the shooting.<ref name = "82t"/>

The defense also presented nine [[Character_witness#Criminal_trials|character witnesses]] including poet [[Sonia Sanchez]]. Sanchez testified that Abu-Jamal was "viewed by the black community as a creative, articulate, peaceful, genial man."<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript p.19
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 30]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-30-82.html#sanchez
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref> During cross examination the prosecution raised the issue of her association with convicted felon and Black Panther activist [[Assata Shakur|Joanne Chesimard]]; Sanchez was also asked over defense objections whether she supported other blacks who had killed police.<ref>{{cite web
 | title = Trial Transcript p.19-30
 | work = Commonwealth v. Mumia Abu-Jamal a.k.a. Wesley Cook
 | publisher =Court of Common Pleas, Philadelphia County, Criminal Trial Division
 | date =[[June 30]], [[1982]]
 | url =http://www.justice4danielfaulkner.com/Days/6-30-82.html#sanchez
 | doi =
 | accessdate = 2007-10-30}}</ref>

=== Witnesses not called at trial ===
{{seealso|Mumia Abu-Jamal legal proceedings#New witnesses}}
Abu-Jamal did not testify in his own defense. Regarding this he has explained:<ref name = "mum">{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =Declaration of Mumia Abu-Jamal
 | work =
 | publisher =Chicago Committee to Free Mumia Abu-Jamal 
 | date =May 2001
 | url =http://www.chicagofreemumia.org/mumiadecl.html 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}</ref><blockquote>"At my trial I was denied the right to defend myself. I had no confidence in my court-appointed attorney, who never even asked me what happened the night I was shot and the police officer was killed; and I was excluded from at least half the trial. Since I was denied all my rights at my trial I did not testify. I would not be used to make it look like I had a fair trial."</blockquote>
He did not state his version of events for the initial police investigation, nor for almost another 20 years afterwards until subsequent to his third set of lawyers offering the 1999 affidavit of [[Arnold Beverly]]. Beverly purported to confess that, "wearing a green (camouflage) army jacket", he had run across the street and shot a fallen Daniel Faulkner in the face as part of a contract killing connected with a desire to keep Faulkner from interfering with graft and payoff to corrupt police.<ref>{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =Affidavit of Arnold Beverly
 | work =
 | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
 | date =[[June 8]], [[1999]] 
 | url =http://www.freemumia.com/beverlydeclaration.html 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}
</ref> 
Abu-Jamal's May 2001 sworn statement avers that he had been sitting in his cab across the street when he first heard shouting, then saw a police vehicle, then heard the sound of gunshots. It further asserts that, upon seeing his brother standing in the street staggering and appearing disoriented he ran across the street to him and was shot by a uniformed police officer. It also incorporates Abu-Jamal's claim to have been tortured by the police while he was still in need of medical assistance for his wounds. It concludes with his claim of innocence: "I never said I shot the policeman. I did not shoot the policeman. I never said I hoped he died. I would never say something like that."<ref name = "mum"/>

For a similar period, William Cook also did not testify or make any statement whatsoever about events other than his utterance at the crimescene, "I ain't got nothing to do with this."<ref>{{cite news 
 | last =Lopez
 | first =Steve
 | coauthors =
 | title =Wrong Guy, Good Cause
 | work =
 | pages =
 | language =
 | publisher =[[Time Magazine]]
 | date =[[July 23]], [[2000]]
 | url =http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,50613,00.html
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}</ref> On [[April 29]], [[2001]], Cook belatedly authored a declaration to the effect that he would be willing to testify and that both he and his brother "had nothing do with shooting or killing the policeman". The statement inculpates [[Kenneth Freeman]] as being armed with a .38 caliber firearm, present in Cook's vehicle passenger seat immediately prior to the confronation with Daniel Faulkner, wearing a green army jacket of a fashion described by as many as four witnesses observing those present at the scene, and admitting to planning to kill Faulkner and participating in his shooting.<ref>{{cite web
 | last =
 | first =
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =
 | title =Declaration of William Cook
 | work =
 | publisher =Free Mumia Coalition
 | date =[[April 29]], [[2001]]
 | url =http://www.freemumia.com/cookdeclaration.html 
 | format =
 | doi =
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}
</ref> Freeman's handcuffed and naked corpse was discovered in a vacant lot in North Philadelphia the day after [[MOVE#Confrontation_Leads_Police_to_Bomb_MOVE_House|the police bombing of the MOVE communal residence in 1985]] and neither his name nor the fact of his presence at the crimescene was raised at any stage during the course of the trial and sentencing in 1982.<ref>{{cite press release
 | title =Jurors Never Saw Earliest Photos at Abu-Jamal’s 1982 Trial - Recent Discovery of 26 Photos Of 
Officer Faulkner's Scene of Death 
 | publisher =Educators for Mumia Abu-Jamal
 | date =[[September 25]], [[2007]]
 | url =http://www.phillyimc.org/en/2007/10/42608.shtml
 | accessdate =2007-10-18 }}</ref> At the time of his death, Daniel Faulkner was in possession of the replacement temporary driver license of [[Arnold Howard]] which the latter had recently "loaned" to Freeman for unspecified purposes.<ref>{{cite book
 | last =Asher
 | first =Robert 
 | authorlink =
 | coauthors =Lawrence B. Goodheart, Alan Rogers
 | title =Murder on Trial: 1620-2002 
 | publisher =[[State University of New York Press]]
 | date =2005
 | location =Albany, New York
 | pages =101
 | url =http://books.google.com/books?id=9bZDdJpQhSEC&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101&dq=kenneth+freeman+driver+license&source=web&ots=5aDwsigTqR&sig=HHyNKc9INqZuVVZpOTqxacpfeEk#PPA64,M1
 | doi =
 | id = 
 | isbn = 0-7914-6378-8}}</ref>
<!-- [[Image:Singchair.jpg|thumb|right|A model of [[electric chair]]. Electrocution was employed as the means of judicial execution of death row prisoners in Pennsylvania from 1915 until [[November 29]], [[1990]].]]copyright status disputed--><ref name = "PAdeathhist">{{cite web
